[WHISPERING INDISTINCTLY]

30
00:02:44,360 --> 00:02:46,635
Youth, uh... Youth Mark eteer.

31
00:02:46,880 --> 00:02:49,075
Here. Take this. Okay.

32
00:02:49,280 --> 00:02:51,032
Hey. How are you?

33
00:03:19,720 --> 00:03:22,154
[PAPER RUSTLES]

34
00:03:38,480 --> 00:03:40,436
Thanks, Chris.

35
00:03:43,480 --> 00:03:46,153
Come on, you wanna help me?
Help me out. I'm a vet.

36
00:03:46,360 --> 00:03:47,588
WOMAN: Hey, watch it!
Come on.

37
00:03:47,840 --> 00:03:49,068
Please don't touch me.
Come on.

38
00:03:49,280 --> 00:03:50,633
Taxi, taxi.

39
00:03:50,840 --> 00:03:53,434
All I want's a quarter, man.
Come on.

40
00:04:07,680 --> 00:04:10,956
Check this out, man.
Step up to the store.

41
00:04:11,160 --> 00:04:13,435
Check this out.

42
00:04:16,080 --> 00:04:18,116
Hey, Marcus, what are
you selling today?

43
00:04:18,320 --> 00:04:22,199
Hey, little sister, check this out.
I got this yesterday.

44
00:04:22,440 --> 00:04:23,998
I like this gold one.
How much is it?

45
00:04:24,200 --> 00:04:25,633
Hey, check the hot tops.

46
00:04:25,840 --> 00:04:28,035
That's my brother, Rand.
Youth Mark eteer.

47
00:04:28,240 --> 00:04:31,437
That's Wall Street for beginners.

48
00:04:37,360 --> 00:04:39,874
What's for dinner?
I'm starving.

49
00:04:40,200 --> 00:04:42,236
It's Tuesday.
That's you, Rand.

50
00:04:42,440 --> 00:04:45,750
Oh, uh, spaghetti. Gina, give me a hand,
will you? I'll help you out tomorrow.

51
00:04:45,960 --> 00:04:47,473
Yeah, sure.

52
00:04:48,080 --> 00:04:50,469
Tough day?
No. The day was fine.

53
00:04:50,680 --> 00:04:55,959
I just wish for once I could get into a cab without
a bunch of psychotics waiting in line to mug me.

54
00:04:56,200 --> 00:04:57,428
[DOORBELL RINGS]

55
00:04:57,680 --> 00:04:59,989
GINA: Oop, I'll get it.
RAND: You're just being paranoid, Dad.

56
00:05:00,200 --> 00:05:02,031
I would rather be paranoid
than be accosted.

57
00:05:02,240 --> 00:05:04,993
Yeah, uh, speaking of money...
DR. THOMPSON: Do we have to?

58
00:05:07,560 --> 00:05:09,949
Here, Dad. This is for you.

59
00:05:10,720 --> 00:05:13,518
Would you mind if I took
dance lessons three times a week?

60
00:05:13,760 --> 00:05:17,196
Aren't you overdoing it?
GINA: I don't think I'm doing it enough.

61
00:05:17,400 --> 00:05:20,631
Yeah, also if I could borrow, like, $700,
I could do my newsletter right here at home.

62
00:05:20,880 --> 00:05:22,552
DR. THOMPSON: I don't believe this.
RAND: What?

63
00:05:22,800 --> 00:05:24,119
The Rosebrook Research Institute.

64
00:05:24,320 --> 00:05:26,356
That one where you stayed up
for, like, three nights in a row?

65
00:05:26,560 --> 00:05:28,630
Writing the grant proposal.
It just came through.

66
00:05:28,840 --> 00:05:30,876
That's cool, Dad.
Congratulations.

67
00:05:31,080 --> 00:05:33,913
Maybe I can subsidize the extra
lesson with your new grant check.

68
00:05:34,120 --> 00:05:37,829
Yeah, listen, uh, Jerry's newsstand wants to
distribute for me, but I don't think it's necessary-

69
00:05:38,080 --> 00:05:39,308
Whoa, whoa, whoa,
you don't understand.

70
00:05:39,520 --> 00:05:41,431
This underwrites my research
for two years.

71
00:05:41,640 --> 00:05:43,437
Is this oregano or thyme?
Oh, that's oregano.

72
00:05:43,680 --> 00:05:47,798
So, which means, boys and girls, we
will be leaving for Africa in two weeks.

73
00:05:48,000 --> 00:05:49,228
Africa?
Africa?

74
00:05:49,480 --> 00:05:50,799
That's where I'm doing the research.

75
00:05:51,000 --> 00:05:52,592
Dad, no.
That's impossible.

76
00:05:52,840 --> 00:05:54,159
Now, wait a minute.
It's only two years.

77
00:05:54,360 --> 00:05:56,669
How many kids do you know
get a chance to go to Africa?

78
00:05:56,880 --> 00:05:58,916
Wait a minute. No, Dad.
Timing here is everything, okay?

79
00:05:59,120 --> 00:06:01,998
You want to go to Africa, that's fine.
You can be my guest.

80
00:06:02,200 --> 00:06:04,634
As for me, I think I'm speaking
for Gina here also,

81
00:06:04,840 --> 00:06:07,718
we got plenty to do right here
in the good old U.S. of A.

82
00:06:08,080 --> 00:06:11,038
There's no way I'm going to Africa.

83
00:06:22,960 --> 00:06:24,598
Rand.

84
00:06:24,840 --> 00:06:26,671
Giraffes.

85
00:06:27,560 --> 00:06:29,152
I've seen giraffes.

86
00:06:47,440 --> 00:06:50,796
[SPEAKING IN FOREIGN LANGU AGE]

87
00:07:32,400 --> 00:07:34,755
This is my wife, Frances,
and our son, Nik Nik.

88
00:07:34,960 --> 00:07:36,473
How do you do, Frances? I'm David.
FRANCES: Hi.

89
00:07:36,680 --> 00:07:37,908
Hello, Nik Nik.
NIK NIK: Hello.

90
00:07:38,120 --> 00:07:39,872
This is my daughter, Gina.
Hi.

91
00:07:40,080 --> 00:07:41,559
DR. THOMPSON: Rand?
GINA: Nice to meet you.

92
00:07:43,240 --> 00:07:44,593
That's my son, Rand.

93
00:07:45,200 --> 00:07:48,829
Papa says we're gonna take good care of
you so you don't get into too much trouble.

94
00:07:49,360 --> 00:07:50,918
DR. THOMPSON: Well, thank you
very much, Nik Nik.

95
00:07:51,120 --> 00:07:54,556
FRANCES: I hope you had a good trip.
GINA: It was a long, long way.

96
00:07:55,120 --> 00:07:59,398
Who are you?
I'm, uh, the Easter Bunny.

97
00:07:59,640 --> 00:08:01,517
I don't think so.
No?

98
00:08:01,760 --> 00:08:04,479
I'll show you to your rooms.
Uh, no, thank you.

99
00:08:04,680 --> 00:08:07,592
I think I'm gonna find
my own place to bunk.

100
00:08:08,160 --> 00:08:12,915
By my calculations, that barn over
there is the closest one to America.

101
00:08:14,560 --> 00:08:18,599
Uh, Rand, in that barn-
It's okay. Let him go.

102
00:08:31,440 --> 00:08:33,510
[RAND GROANS]

103
00:08:33,920 --> 00:08:35,558
[GROWLS]

104
00:08:37,840 --> 00:08:39,068
RAND:
Oh, no.

105
00:08:40,880 --> 00:08:42,552
Okay.

106
00:08:43,440 --> 00:08:45,510
All right. Oh, no.

107
00:08:46,000 --> 00:08:50,551
Easy, easy there.
There you go. All right. Yeah.

108
00:08:51,440 --> 00:08:53,829
Boy, you're big.

109
00:09:05,200 --> 00:09:07,236
There you are.

110
00:09:08,000 --> 00:09:09,718
Sorry. She likes this barn.

111
00:09:11,840 --> 00:09:14,593
That is a lion.
Yes, it is.

112
00:09:14,840 --> 00:09:17,638
It's all right. Elsa's quite tame.

113
00:09:18,040 --> 00:09:22,192
I'm Val Porter. Mother and I live down
the hill. You must be the new neighbors.

114
00:09:22,440 --> 00:09:25,477
Yes. I'm, uh, Dr. Thompson.

115
00:09:25,680 --> 00:09:28,148
These are my children,
Gina and Rand.

116
00:09:28,600 --> 00:09:31,114
It's all right. Nearly everyone's
a little frightened at first.

117
00:09:31,360 --> 00:09:35,194
Lady, it's, uh...
It's gonna take a lot more

118
00:09:35,400 --> 00:09:38,676
than a big pussycat to frighten me.

119
00:09:38,920 --> 00:09:40,797
Obviously.

120
00:09:54,480 --> 00:09:56,471
I think she likes you.

121
00:09:57,200 --> 00:10:00,078
RAND: Who, the ice maiden
or the man-eater?

122
00:10:13,600 --> 00:10:14,999
Where was she?

123
00:10:15,200 --> 00:10:17,873
In the barn, scaring
the new people.

124
00:10:19,680 --> 00:10:21,955
Dr. Thompson wonder
where I was?

125
00:10:22,160 --> 00:10:24,799
He didn't ask about you at all.

126
00:10:28,800 --> 00:10:31,792
There was a daughter and a son,
and for some weird reason,

127
00:10:32,000 --> 00:10:34,230
Elsa got an immediate
crush on the son.

128
00:10:34,440 --> 00:10:36,908
Uh-oh. Jealous?

129
00:10:37,120 --> 00:10:39,998
Elsa can like
whomever she pleases.

130
00:10:40,360 --> 00:10:42,920
I meant the other way around.

131
00:10:43,120 --> 00:10:46,271
Oh, no. He's not my type at all.

132
00:10:46,480 --> 00:10:51,315
Thinks he's something special.
I can't stand that kind of arrogance.

133
00:11:00,560 --> 00:11:02,790
[SQUEALS]

134
00:11:10,320 --> 00:11:11,719
[MUSIC TURNS OFF]

135
00:11:11,960 --> 00:11:14,235
[ANIMAL CRIES]

136
00:11:25,320 --> 00:11:26,992
Got to admit that was cool.

137
00:11:38,760 --> 00:11:41,513
So I guess you were thinking
of settling out here.

138
00:11:41,720 --> 00:11:43,711
Yeah, I'd like to.

139
00:11:45,360 --> 00:11:48,989
Well, I don't know
about this, Rand.

140
00:11:49,200 --> 00:11:52,715
There could be wild animals
or snakes at night.

141
00:11:53,160 --> 00:11:55,720
I'm not bothering
anybody out here,

142
00:11:55,920 --> 00:11:57,831
and I'll keep the place clean.

143
00:11:58,040 --> 00:12:00,031
Well, oh, okay.

144
00:12:01,520 --> 00:12:04,876
I wish you wouldn't separate
yourself from us. That's all.

145
00:12:05,640 --> 00:12:08,712
I'd prefer it out here. If you
tell me to go back inside...

146
00:12:08,920 --> 00:12:12,674
I'm not telling you you have to.
It's not an order, just a wish.

147
00:12:23,960 --> 00:12:26,155
FRANCES: Is something wrong
with American fries?

148
00:12:26,360 --> 00:12:29,079
Oh, no. They're perfect.
They're wonderful.

149
00:12:29,320 --> 00:12:32,232
Could I fix you a sandwich or a salad?
Nope. Not a thing, Frances.

150
00:12:32,440 --> 00:12:35,830
But we'll do better by your food
when we've rested. Promise.

151
00:12:36,040 --> 00:12:37,678
Okay.

152
00:12:40,800 --> 00:12:44,076
It's incredible, isn't it?
Mm.

153
00:12:44,960 --> 00:12:46,188
Mm-hm.

154
00:12:46,800 --> 00:12:49,268
Look, Gina, I know this isn't easy.

155
00:12:49,480 --> 00:12:51,869
Things will get better when
Rand comes around a little.

156
00:12:52,080 --> 00:12:53,957
I don't know
what's gotten into him.

157
00:12:56,800 --> 00:12:58,472
Gina?

158
00:13:25,840 --> 00:13:29,355
[SPEAKING INDISTINCTLY]

159
00:13:42,320 --> 00:13:44,914
[LOUD MUSIC PLAYING]

160
00:13:47,440 --> 00:13:50,512
[MUSIC DISTORTS, THEN STOPS]

161
00:13:52,200 --> 00:13:54,191
Oh, man.

162
00:14:08,360 --> 00:14:10,555
[GROWLING]

163
00:14:17,600 --> 00:14:19,909
Hey, pussycat.

164
00:14:36,200 --> 00:14:37,679
How's Winny doing?

165
00:14:37,880 --> 00:14:40,838
She won't eat unless I feed her.
Oh.

166
00:14:42,920 --> 00:14:44,797
Winny would make a nice pet.

167
00:14:45,000 --> 00:14:48,310
Well, I have a pet, on
permanent loan, apparently.

168
00:14:48,520 --> 00:14:52,638
No, Val. You're keeping
a lion for George Luello.

169
00:14:52,840 --> 00:14:54,432
GEORGE: Good morning.
Speaking of whom.

170
00:14:54,640 --> 00:14:55,868
Good morning, George.
Good morning.

171
00:14:56,080 --> 00:14:58,958
Val, I need you to
fill this out, please.

172
00:14:59,160 --> 00:15:00,513
It's the keeper's report.

173
00:15:00,720 --> 00:15:03,109
A summary of Elsa's behavior and
habits while she's been in your care.

174
00:15:03,320 --> 00:15:05,117
You're taking her away?
Not now, Val.

175
00:15:05,320 --> 00:15:07,197
But it's coming.
You know that.

176
00:15:20,520 --> 00:15:22,750
Now comes the hard part.

177
00:15:42,560 --> 00:15:45,711
[GROWLING]

178
00:15:51,400 --> 00:15:53,118
Good morning.

179
00:16:00,160 --> 00:16:02,196
So, uh...

180
00:16:02,480 --> 00:16:06,758
this is your place? This is your
barn? This is where you live, huh?

181
00:16:07,760 --> 00:16:09,432
Well...

182
00:16:09,640 --> 00:16:11,392
I'm just...

183
00:16:12,800 --> 00:16:15,075
I'm just gonna get dressed.

184
00:16:16,120 --> 00:16:18,554
I'm gonna go in the kitchen...

185
00:16:18,760 --> 00:16:21,797
and have some breakfast.

186
00:16:26,440 --> 00:16:29,398
All right. Just take it easy,
all right? I'll just, uh...

187
00:16:29,600 --> 00:16:30,828
I'll go out this way.

188
00:16:33,480 --> 00:16:35,516
What is the problem?

189
00:16:37,720 --> 00:16:39,073
[GUN SHOOTS]

190
00:16:43,800 --> 00:16:45,552
What?

191
00:16:50,920 --> 00:16:53,878
Good morning.
I see your watchdog alerted you.

192
00:16:57,240 --> 00:16:59,549
You're trying to say that she
was protecting me from that thing?

193
00:16:59,760 --> 00:17:02,832
Egyptian cobra. Very deadly.

194
00:17:04,600 --> 00:17:06,352
What happened?

195
00:17:06,560 --> 00:17:09,518
Is that snake poisonous?
No. Dad, it's fine. Really.

196
00:17:09,760 --> 00:17:12,274
I think you're gonna have to forget
about sleeping in the barn, Rand.

197
00:17:12,520 --> 00:17:14,556
Dad, it's nothing. Forget it-
No, it's okay,

198
00:17:14,760 --> 00:17:16,398
Dr. Thompson, it's all right.

199
00:17:16,600 --> 00:17:20,479
Elsa is the very best protection you
can find. She doesn't miss a thing.

200
00:17:20,920 --> 00:17:23,514
And I don't mind her staying
out here with your son,

201
00:17:23,720 --> 00:17:26,029
since, for some reason,
she likes it.

202
00:17:30,640 --> 00:17:32,551
Good girl.

203
00:17:32,960 --> 00:17:35,918
Stay here. Good girl.

204
00:17:41,640 --> 00:17:43,517
Ready, Nik Nik?
Yeah, I'm ready.

205
00:17:43,760 --> 00:17:45,876
FRANCES: All right.
VAL: Bye.

206
00:17:46,120 --> 00:17:47,951
Bye.
NIK NIK: Bye-bye.

207
00:18:00,000 --> 00:18:01,399
Ah.

208
00:18:01,600 --> 00:18:03,909
I'm from Greystone Academy.
I'm here to see-

209
00:18:04,120 --> 00:18:07,271
I know, I know. Actually, you're here
early. I didn't expect you till tomorrow.

210
00:18:07,480 --> 00:18:10,836
GINA: Greystone Academy?
RAND: What is this, Dad?

211
00:18:11,160 --> 00:18:14,152
Uh, yes, I meant to discuss this with you
earlier, but with everything happening,

212
00:18:14,360 --> 00:18:17,557
I thought we'd settle down a little.
Greystone's is the best school in the country.

213
00:18:17,800 --> 00:18:19,677
Where is it?
It's in the capital.

214
00:18:19,880 --> 00:18:21,313
The capital’s two hours from here.

215
00:18:21,520 --> 00:18:24,398
You're shipping us off to some
boarding school halfway across Africa?

216
00:18:24,640 --> 00:18:27,313
I am not shipping- Look, this is
the way things are done here.

217
00:18:27,520 --> 00:18:30,432
Greystone's happens to be
the finest school in the country here.

218
00:18:30,640 --> 00:18:32,153
And I think you're awful lucky
to get in.

219
00:18:32,400 --> 00:18:34,197
Do you hear that, Gina?
You feel lucky?

220
00:18:34,400 --> 00:18:36,436
Now wait a minute. Don't start now.
No, well, I certainly feel lucky.

221
00:18:36,680 --> 00:18:38,079
You know, I feel lucky.
I feel very lucky.

222
00:18:38,280 --> 00:18:42,034
We've just been subjected to another
one of Dad's dead-end ultimatums.

223
00:18:42,240 --> 00:18:43,514
"You're going to Africa. "
No discussion.

224
00:18:43,720 --> 00:18:46,951
"You're leaving your friends, your home, everything
you care about for two years. " No discussion.

225
00:18:47,200 --> 00:18:49,998
" Now it's off to some boarding school
you know nothing about. " No discussion.

226
00:18:50,200 --> 00:18:52,475
Now, hold on, Rand. I did mean
to discuss this with you.

227
00:18:52,680 --> 00:18:57,117
You know, the thing is, you haven't discussed
anything with us. That's the problem, okay? Because...

228
00:18:57,320 --> 00:18:59,197
Look, Gina and I want
a chance to be adults.

229
00:18:59,400 --> 00:19:03,154
We wanna have something to say about where we
live, how we live. But no, you treat us like babies.

230
00:19:03,360 --> 00:19:05,351
Why are we in Africa, Dad?
Because we sat down and discussed

231
00:19:05,560 --> 00:19:07,198
the pros and cons
like three equals? No.

232
00:19:07,400 --> 00:19:09,709
We're not equals.
I'm the parent, you're the kid.

233
00:19:09,960 --> 00:19:13,236
Real- Okay, that's good.
That's real good. All right.

234
00:19:19,400 --> 00:19:21,630
Well, all right. I've been arbitrary.

235
00:19:21,840 --> 00:19:24,912
But we're here. There's nothing
we can do about it. We are in Africa.

236
00:19:25,120 --> 00:19:27,509
We are in Africa, Rand. And that's
the most appropriate school.

237
00:19:27,720 --> 00:19:30,029
And that's where I want you to go.
I've thoroughly researched this.

238
00:19:30,320 --> 00:19:32,356
Well, where does Val go?
And Nik Nik?

239
00:19:32,600 --> 00:19:34,830
Where are those kids going?

240
00:19:35,320 --> 00:19:38,471
To Shamba School.
The only one here.

241
00:19:38,680 --> 00:19:41,274
Yes, well, it's not anything
you'd really be accustomed to.

242
00:19:41,520 --> 00:19:45,479
Is it a good school?
Shamba School is a very good school

243
00:19:45,680 --> 00:19:47,159
for Val and Nik Nik.

244
00:19:48,120 --> 00:19:51,078
Well, if it's good enough for Val
and Nik Nik, it's good enough for me.

245
00:19:51,280 --> 00:19:53,157
Count me in.

246
00:20:01,800 --> 00:20:03,438
Where's the school?

247
00:20:04,480 --> 00:20:07,472
Jomo says it's about two miles
that way on the left.

248
00:20:07,680 --> 00:20:10,478
You better get started. You're already
late. I'll be by later to check it out.

249
00:20:10,680 --> 00:20:13,831
Two miles? You could zip us down
there in a minute and a half.

250
00:20:14,040 --> 00:20:17,999
Well, I'm sorry, but I'm late too.
And you could use the exercise.

251
00:20:18,200 --> 00:20:22,318
After all, if it's good enough
for Val and Nik Nik...

252
00:20:22,520 --> 00:20:24,829
You see that? That's right.

253
00:20:25,040 --> 00:20:28,635
You had to throw that in, didn't you? Now we're
gonna be hearing that every time we turn around.

254
00:20:28,840 --> 00:20:30,637
"That's right, if it's good enough
for Val and Nik Nik... "

255
00:20:30,840 --> 00:20:34,549
Look, at least I made something happen
instead of just standing there, complaining.

256
00:20:34,760 --> 00:20:36,478
Okay, you know, um...

257
00:20:42,000 --> 00:20:43,228
Hello.

258
00:20:43,440 --> 00:20:45,237
[SPEAK IN FOREIGN LANGU AGE]

259
00:20:48,160 --> 00:20:49,878
Miss Porter.

260
00:20:52,120 --> 00:20:54,350
Eleanor.

261
00:20:59,720 --> 00:21:02,188
Dr. Thompson.
David.

262
00:21:02,400 --> 00:21:05,949
Actually, I met your daughter.
Twice already.

263
00:21:09,400 --> 00:21:11,595
[SPEAKS IN FOREIGN LANGU AGE]

264
00:21:12,560 --> 00:21:13,834
Uh, this way.

265
00:21:14,040 --> 00:21:15,917
Okay.

266
00:21:16,520 --> 00:21:18,556
ELEANOR: As you can see,
we get by on very little.

267
00:21:18,800 --> 00:21:24,238
On the other hand, you'll be happy to know
we do have a wealth of viruses to study.

268
00:21:28,120 --> 00:21:29,997
[SPEAKS IN FOREIGN LANGU AGE]

269
00:21:32,280 --> 00:21:34,953
Their temperature
stays over 103,

270
00:21:35,160 --> 00:21:38,709
and their surface symptoms,
well, they're all over the map.

271
00:21:40,040 --> 00:21:41,712
I'm going to need
blood samples.

272
00:21:41,920 --> 00:21:45,708
Dr. Thompson, I'm afraid you're gonna be on your
own for a while. I've got to see to my patients.

273
00:21:47,680 --> 00:21:50,752
The lab is just through there.
Such as it is.

274
00:21:52,760 --> 00:21:53,988
[THOMPSON CLEARS THROAT]

275
00:21:54,240 --> 00:21:57,357
Oh, that's the, uh, lab?

276
00:21:57,560 --> 00:21:59,357
Yes.
Uh-huh.

277
00:22:00,800 --> 00:22:03,917
I'm afraid no one had the time
to fix it up for you.

278
00:22:21,520 --> 00:22:23,590
RAND: That's the school?
Oh, neat.

279
00:22:23,800 --> 00:22:25,711
It looks just like play school.

280
00:22:25,920 --> 00:22:28,753
Yeah, be careful. By lunchtime, they'll
have you making lamps and billfolds

281
00:22:28,960 --> 00:22:31,315
out of Popsicle sticks.

282
00:22:43,760 --> 00:22:46,479
Doctor, progress?

283
00:22:46,680 --> 00:22:49,240
Officially the viral samples
are the same,

284
00:22:49,440 --> 00:22:51,590
but around the edges,

285
00:22:51,800 --> 00:22:54,155
there is a difference.

286
00:22:54,520 --> 00:22:57,956
I just can't get a clear view
with this piece of...

287
00:22:58,160 --> 00:22:59,798
antiquity.

288
00:23:00,880 --> 00:23:02,598
Excuse me.

289
00:23:04,480 --> 00:23:08,632
Uh, well, you could try contacting Jim Willery
in the capital. He might dig something up.

290
00:23:08,840 --> 00:23:11,035
There's no money
in the grant for supplies.

291
00:23:11,240 --> 00:23:14,550
Maybe on the strength of your name.
Dr. David Thompson in Africa.

292
00:23:14,760 --> 00:23:17,069
It's been raising eyebrows
everywhere.

293
00:23:17,280 --> 00:23:19,794
I'm a little surprised myself.

294
00:23:21,640 --> 00:23:26,077
No one knew African viruses
were a special interest for you.

295
00:23:26,320 --> 00:23:28,231
A virus...

296
00:23:28,800 --> 00:23:30,756
is a virus.

297
00:23:32,080 --> 00:23:34,310
And as a place
for my family to live,

298
00:23:34,520 --> 00:23:36,317
Africa was very appealing.

299
00:23:38,760 --> 00:23:40,432
Excuse me.

300
00:23:59,680 --> 00:24:04,151
Oh, uh, excuse me.
Could I have one word with you?

301
00:24:07,080 --> 00:24:08,672
That's your domain in there,

302
00:24:08,880 --> 00:24:11,599
and I know it must feel
like I'm invading.

303
00:24:11,800 --> 00:24:14,678
But can I assure you
that's not my intention.

304
00:24:15,160 --> 00:24:17,879
Selena Wilkinson,
born and raised nearby,

305
00:24:18,080 --> 00:24:21,117
had been doing brilliant research
here and in Zaire.

306
00:24:21,320 --> 00:24:26,269
For years, she's been praying for the
kind of grant they simply handed you.

307
00:24:26,480 --> 00:24:29,552
It would have been the
culmination of a lifetime's work,

308
00:24:29,760 --> 00:24:32,752
not just a free safari
for some children.

309
00:24:33,240 --> 00:24:34,958
Miss Porter...

310
00:24:35,600 --> 00:24:38,751
I am sorry about your
friend's disappointment.

311
00:24:38,960 --> 00:24:41,793
I came to Africa to work
and to work hard.

312
00:24:42,000 --> 00:24:45,470
If my having a double motive
disqualifies me in your book, well,

313
00:24:45,680 --> 00:24:47,750
that's going to make it
a little bit tough for both of us,

314
00:24:47,960 --> 00:24:51,157
but that is something that
you will have to live with.

315
00:24:57,840 --> 00:25:01,071
So as Africans, how do you feel?

316
00:25:01,280 --> 00:25:04,397
Do you think the power should lie
with any one nation?

317
00:25:04,640 --> 00:25:08,997
Well, ma'am, it seems to me that no one
country should control nuclear power.

318
00:25:09,200 --> 00:25:12,670
Uh-huh, and how would
you have it be, Neuru?

319
00:25:12,880 --> 00:25:15,713
The way I see it is that
the United Nations should take over

320
00:25:15,920 --> 00:25:18,718
and say where it can be used
and, I suppose, where it can't.

321
00:25:19,600 --> 00:25:22,512
Let's hear from one
of our newcomers.

322
00:25:22,720 --> 00:25:24,438
Rand.

323
00:25:24,680 --> 00:25:26,830
What's your opinion?

324
00:25:27,160 --> 00:25:31,551
Sitting out here in the middle of nowhere,
I don't think you need to be too concerned.

325
00:25:32,600 --> 00:25:35,751
Nobody's gonna waste
a warhead on this place.

326
00:25:39,080 --> 00:25:43,756
You will find, Rand, that out here
in the middle of nowhere,

327
00:25:43,960 --> 00:25:46,952
we don't see ourselves
as third-class. In fact,

328
00:25:47,160 --> 00:25:51,119
we have the same rights and responsibilities
as Americans in the biggest cities.

329
00:25:51,320 --> 00:25:53,959
That's another world, Miss Luello.

330
00:25:54,200 --> 00:25:56,395
Oh, yes. Yes, it is, Rand.

331
00:25:56,640 --> 00:26:00,189
Miss Luello got her MA
at Columbia.

332
00:26:00,400 --> 00:26:03,836
And how long have you been
in Africa for, American boy?

333
00:26:04,040 --> 00:26:07,191
What? One day? And already
you know everything about us?

334
00:26:07,440 --> 00:26:09,192
That's enough, Neuru.
Okay.

335
00:26:09,400 --> 00:26:12,278
I won't waste any more
of your time or mine.

336
00:26:12,520 --> 00:26:14,033
Rand, sit down, please.

337
00:26:15,920 --> 00:26:17,876
Rand.

338
00:26:18,600 --> 00:26:21,160
Sit down.

339
00:26:58,200 --> 00:27:03,718
Dr. Thompson, I'm, uh... I'm finishing
up early. Would you like some help?

340
00:27:03,920 --> 00:27:06,480
Oh, no. No, I'm fine. Thanks.

341
00:27:21,000 --> 00:27:23,116
I'm going to Vail’s, okay?

342
00:27:23,320 --> 00:27:25,470
NIK NIK: Bye.
GIRLS: Bye.

343
00:27:26,000 --> 00:27:28,195
Good. Now it's just us men.

344
00:27:28,400 --> 00:27:30,709
I've got things to do,
okay, Nik Nik?

345
00:27:30,920 --> 00:27:33,718
I'll help you.
Oh, yeah?

346
00:27:33,920 --> 00:27:35,990
How can you help me?

347
00:27:36,280 --> 00:27:40,319
Well, I'll tell you never to stand
on an anthill. They bite.

348
00:27:40,560 --> 00:27:44,917
Oh, no. Okay.
Get them off. Get them off.

349
00:27:48,240 --> 00:27:50,356
Let me help you up.

350
00:27:50,840 --> 00:27:53,274
You see, I'm a good guy
to have around.

351
00:27:55,880 --> 00:27:58,394
RAND: Good guy to have around,
but you can't beat me up the hill.

352
00:27:58,600 --> 00:28:03,355
You want to race?
Wanna go? Good. Come on.

353
00:28:03,760 --> 00:28:06,558
[BLEATING]

354
00:28:06,800 --> 00:28:07,994
[WHISTLES]

355
00:28:08,200 --> 00:28:10,156
[GROWLING]

356
00:28:28,760 --> 00:28:30,637
Elsa.

357
00:28:38,960 --> 00:28:40,439
George.

358
00:28:40,640 --> 00:28:42,949
Yes, Magilla.

359
00:28:44,800 --> 00:28:48,588
You know, it's not so smart to
have her hanging around your goats.

360
00:28:49,160 --> 00:28:51,390
Oh, come on, George.
She doesn't hurt them.

361
00:28:51,600 --> 00:28:54,558
Mm-mm. Elsa's a lion.

362
00:28:54,760 --> 00:28:57,149
She doesn't act much like it now,
but one day she will.

363
00:28:57,360 --> 00:29:02,354
Relax, George. She's wonderful.
Yes, Magilla, but she's still a lion.

364
00:29:08,080 --> 00:29:10,150
Still working?

365
00:29:10,360 --> 00:29:12,794
No. I'm... I'm playing chess.

366
00:29:21,600 --> 00:29:23,352
Since when are you
afraid of Elsa?

367
00:29:23,960 --> 00:29:27,396
It's dinnertime. She's hungry,
and I'm little.

368
00:29:27,640 --> 00:29:30,200
Well, I don't have
any food, girl.

369
00:29:30,680 --> 00:29:32,716
What is she doing, Nik Nik?
What does she want?

370
00:29:33,080 --> 00:29:34,308
She likes you.

371
00:29:35,960 --> 00:29:37,712
RAND:
Likes me, really?

372
00:29:38,440 --> 00:29:39,668
You're lucky.

373
00:29:40,400 --> 00:29:41,879
Hey.

374
00:29:42,680 --> 00:29:44,671
Hey there. Yeah.

375
00:29:44,880 --> 00:29:47,519
You're friendly. Hey.

376
00:29:48,840 --> 00:29:52,150
NIK NIK:
Rand! Rand!

377
00:29:52,360 --> 00:29:54,316
Rand!

378
00:29:54,520 --> 00:29:56,556
He's not down there.

379
00:29:56,760 --> 00:29:58,796
Well, we should have left
10 minutes ago.

380
00:29:59,000 --> 00:30:01,753
All right, go on ahead,
and I'll send him down.

381
00:30:14,480 --> 00:30:17,631
RAND: Hey, come on. Show some respect.
That's my friend you're insulting.

382
00:30:19,440 --> 00:30:21,078
Okay, run up there, all right?

383
00:30:21,280 --> 00:30:24,670
One, two, three.

384
00:30:37,480 --> 00:30:39,357
You're a showoff.

385
00:30:39,560 --> 00:30:41,357
You also have four legs.

386
00:31:11,920 --> 00:31:13,956
I thought you were fast.

387
00:31:17,080 --> 00:31:18,718
What happened?

388
00:31:18,920 --> 00:31:20,797
[LAUGHS]

389
00:31:36,760 --> 00:31:38,876
Rand, where have you been?

390
00:31:39,800 --> 00:31:44,510
I, uh, took a hike.
Actually, Elsa took me on a hike.

391
00:31:44,720 --> 00:31:47,518
Actually, you skipped school.
That is unacceptable.

392
00:31:47,720 --> 00:31:49,312
Dad, this school is
a complete waste of time.

393
00:31:49,520 --> 00:31:51,670
Oh, no, no. You could have
gone to Greystone's.

394
00:31:51,880 --> 00:31:53,108
Greystone wouldn't
have been any better.

395
00:31:53,320 --> 00:31:54,719
Nothing would be better
for you right now, Rand.

396
00:31:54,920 --> 00:31:58,833
I know you, and from now on, you will
attend every class unless I excuse you.

397
00:31:59,040 --> 00:32:00,234
Dad, this is not-
No, no.

398
00:32:00,440 --> 00:32:01,668
There is not a negotiation here.

399
00:32:01,880 --> 00:32:03,916
If you skip again,
you'll move back into the house.

400
00:32:04,120 --> 00:32:07,510
I will take away your allowance,
and I will take away that computer.

401
00:32:07,720 --> 00:32:10,678
Oh, really? Okay, you know what? That's
fine with me. Just go ahead and take it.

402
00:32:10,880 --> 00:32:15,317
The freaking batteries are failing. The stupid
African plugs won't fit it. Just go ahead and take it.

403
00:32:15,520 --> 00:32:18,557
You used to be a pretty nice guy
when Mom was still alive.

404
00:32:21,720 --> 00:32:24,188
What was that?
Nothing.

405
00:32:27,360 --> 00:32:29,794
No. I'd like to know
what you said.

406
00:32:31,480 --> 00:32:33,471
I said...

407
00:32:35,360 --> 00:32:38,796
you used to be a pretty nice guy
when Mom was alive.

408
00:32:39,000 --> 00:32:40,877
That's what I said.

409
00:33:05,680 --> 00:33:08,035
RAND:
School, school, school, school.

410
00:33:08,240 --> 00:33:11,391
You know, back home
I liked school. Here?

411
00:33:12,480 --> 00:33:17,031
Well, I learn more fooling around with
you than I would a month in that classroom.

412
00:33:17,760 --> 00:33:21,469
My father and his twisted ideals.
Never knew your father, did you?

413
00:33:21,680 --> 00:33:23,910
Or your mother? No?

414
00:33:24,120 --> 00:33:28,159
My mother...
My mother was something else.

415
00:33:28,920 --> 00:33:33,436
She sure was. She, uh,
treated me like a person.

416
00:33:48,600 --> 00:33:50,670
Elsa, stay!

417
00:33:55,160 --> 00:33:57,151
Why can't she come
to school with us?

418
00:33:57,360 --> 00:34:00,989
She's gotten too big. She gets
into trouble, and she scares people.

419
00:34:01,200 --> 00:34:06,513
Papa says it's time for the zoo.
Please don't discuss that.

420
00:34:31,440 --> 00:34:33,829
Good morning.
Good morning.

421
00:34:34,040 --> 00:34:37,919
We seem to have gotten off on the
wrong foot. I think I said some things

422
00:34:38,120 --> 00:34:39,917
that were unprofessional.

423
00:34:40,120 --> 00:34:43,590
Oh, there's no need to apologize.
I wasn't apologizing.

424
00:34:47,120 --> 00:34:49,680
Miss Porter, I know you resent
my being here.

425
00:34:49,880 --> 00:34:52,030
There's no need
to refer to it any longer.

426
00:34:52,240 --> 00:34:55,471
I am perfectly capable of being civil,
as I hope you are.

427
00:34:55,720 --> 00:34:59,110
There's no reason that we can't
work together. And speaking of work,

428
00:34:59,320 --> 00:35:02,790
I need blood samples of viral patients
every morning and every evening.

429
00:35:03,000 --> 00:35:05,992
And if there are any survivors from
past viral epidemics in this area,

430
00:35:06,200 --> 00:35:10,830
I want to test them, but most of all, somehow,
somewhere, I've got to get a 20th century microscope.

431
00:35:11,040 --> 00:35:14,999
Dr. Thompson, I'm very interested in
your research, and I'm very anxious

432
00:35:15,200 --> 00:35:17,953
to help you in any way I can.
But there's some confusion here.

433
00:35:18,200 --> 00:35:21,590
I am not a part of your grant.
I am not your assistant.

434
00:35:21,800 --> 00:35:25,349
I'm a nurse practitioner,
and my job is to run that clinic.

435
00:35:25,680 --> 00:35:30,196
I think your work is important
and exciting, and I was...

436
00:35:31,120 --> 00:35:34,715
Well, I was hoping to get off
to a fresh start today.

437
00:35:34,920 --> 00:35:37,753
[THUNDER CRASHES]

438
00:35:44,680 --> 00:35:49,913
The end of the 19th century saw a
large expansion in African colonization.

439
00:35:50,120 --> 00:35:53,351
Which of the European powers
held colonies here?

440
00:35:53,560 --> 00:35:54,959
Great Britain.
BO Y: France.

441
00:35:55,160 --> 00:35:58,357
GIRL: Belgium.
Any others?

442
00:35:59,040 --> 00:36:00,871
Rand?
Germany.

443
00:36:02,080 --> 00:36:05,868
Yes. And who were the leaders
of those countries? Anyone?

444
00:36:06,080 --> 00:36:07,638
Queen Victoria in England.

445
00:36:10,280 --> 00:36:13,397
France? Belgium? Germany?

446
00:36:17,920 --> 00:36:19,399
Rand?

447
00:36:21,480 --> 00:36:24,870
Napoleon III in France,
King Leopold in Belgium,

448
00:36:25,080 --> 00:36:29,392
Kaiser Wilhelm I in Germany.
But Bismarck had the real juice.

449
00:36:31,880 --> 00:36:35,839
Thank you. I believe that's lunch.

450
00:36:38,360 --> 00:36:41,193
Rand, could I have
a word with you, please?

451
00:36:49,840 --> 00:36:53,150
I'm glad to have a student
like you with us, Rand.

452
00:36:53,360 --> 00:36:55,396
I just wish you didn't
resent being here.

453
00:36:56,920 --> 00:37:01,675
I answer when you call on me,
and I stay awake.

454
00:37:01,920 --> 00:37:04,878
The minimum. I want more.

455
00:37:05,120 --> 00:37:08,476
You could make
a big contribution if you try.

456
00:37:09,200 --> 00:37:10,952
I'm going back to the States soon.

457
00:37:11,160 --> 00:37:13,674
I've got a lot happening there,
maybe even a job.

458
00:37:13,880 --> 00:37:16,553
What is it that you can do there
that you can't do here?

459
00:37:16,800 --> 00:37:18,756
Oh, oh, uh...

460
00:37:19,160 --> 00:37:22,709
Well, I can hang with my friends.
Take in a band at the Dub Club,

461
00:37:22,920 --> 00:37:26,117
go to the museum, the symphony,
publish The Mark eteer.

462
00:37:26,360 --> 00:37:27,679
The Mark eteer?

463
00:37:29,200 --> 00:37:33,432
Wall Street for my generation. The old guys think the
stock market's some kind of big deal, but it's not.

464
00:37:34,040 --> 00:37:36,076
Well, you make
investments yourself?

465
00:37:37,400 --> 00:37:42,076
Well, Dad says not till I'm 18, so
it's play money. But I'm cleaning up.

466
00:37:43,200 --> 00:37:45,634
I've always hoped
for a school paper.

467
00:37:48,360 --> 00:37:49,793
That's not the same.

468
00:37:52,000 --> 00:37:53,115
Think about it.

469
00:38:12,000 --> 00:38:15,515
That's really good.
Oh, it's just a rough sketch.

470
00:38:15,920 --> 00:38:18,309
I've seen that look
in her eyes a few times.

471
00:38:18,520 --> 00:38:21,159
Yeah. I bet you have.

472
00:38:23,000 --> 00:38:27,232
Listen, Val, I'm not trying to make
her hang out with me or anything.

473
00:38:27,440 --> 00:38:30,113
I know. Thanks.
She's your lion.

474
00:38:30,520 --> 00:38:34,957
No, she's not. No,
she's not mine or anybody's.

475
00:38:35,160 --> 00:38:37,310
But I appreciate the thought.

476
00:38:42,360 --> 00:38:44,237
Oh, here.

477
00:38:44,920 --> 00:38:47,912
No, I don't want it.
You keep it.

478
00:38:50,960 --> 00:38:53,793
Thanks. I will.

479
00:38:56,760 --> 00:39:00,912
[SINGING]

480
00:39:04,200 --> 00:39:08,751
Sorry. Was I singing?
And dancing.

481
00:39:08,960 --> 00:39:11,872
Yeah. Nik Nik says you're going
to be a professional.

482
00:39:12,080 --> 00:39:14,071
Well, I said that,
but I changed my mind.

483
00:39:14,280 --> 00:39:16,430
I mean, there's gotta be
more to life than practice, right?

484
00:39:16,640 --> 00:39:17,868
Maybe.
Maybe.

485
00:39:18,080 --> 00:39:19,911
Here. Listen.

486
00:39:23,240 --> 00:39:25,071
This is cool music.

487
00:39:26,760 --> 00:39:28,193
Rand.

488
00:39:28,640 --> 00:39:32,315
Miss Luello tells me that you are
thinking of starting a school paper?

489
00:39:33,240 --> 00:39:36,232
I said I'd think about it.
And have you?

490
00:39:36,840 --> 00:39:40,628
Have I what?
Thought about it?

491
00:39:40,880 --> 00:39:45,431
You see, I'm interested in the school
paper myself. And since it was your idea,

492
00:39:45,640 --> 00:39:49,838
you are in charge.
That's if you are interested.

493
00:39:50,280 --> 00:39:52,510
But if you are not...

494
00:39:57,560 --> 00:40:01,235
[TYPEWRITER TYPING]

495
00:40:04,080 --> 00:40:06,275
Will everyone in school get a copy?
If they want it.

496
00:40:06,480 --> 00:40:08,948
Here, try this paragraph again.
For free?

497
00:40:09,160 --> 00:40:12,869
First issue, yes.
The first issue is always free.

498
00:40:13,080 --> 00:40:15,355
Why are you calling it
The Termite?

499
00:40:15,560 --> 00:40:20,953
That is the function of a good paper,
to eat away rotten, old-age ideas.

500
00:40:21,160 --> 00:40:23,674
Like a termite.

501
00:40:23,880 --> 00:40:28,954
RAND: So come on. Get your copy of
it right here, right now. Here it is.

502
00:40:41,600 --> 00:40:43,113
MISS LUELLO:
The Termite?

503
00:40:43,720 --> 00:40:45,836
I'll admit the title
is a bit corny.

504
00:40:46,760 --> 00:40:49,911
I had something less
controversial in mind.

505
00:40:50,320 --> 00:40:52,550
Oh, well, "controversial"
is Rand's middle name.

506
00:40:52,760 --> 00:40:55,718
Although, I will say he's
outdone himself this time.

507
00:40:55,920 --> 00:40:58,070
You asked me to publish
a school paper.

508
00:40:58,320 --> 00:41:02,108
I asked you to think about it.
I thought about it, and I did it.

509
00:41:02,360 --> 00:41:03,759
All by yourself.

510
00:41:04,560 --> 00:41:07,950
No, I got Neuru involved.
Typing your essays.

511
00:41:08,200 --> 00:41:14,150
No. You see, his stuff was
a bit naive. No offence, Neuru.

512
00:41:14,360 --> 00:41:19,480
His "stuff," as you call it,
is just as valid as yours.

513
00:41:19,680 --> 00:41:23,639
Maybe I misjudged your editorial
abilities or your maturity.

514
00:41:23,880 --> 00:41:25,518
So I guess you'll have
to expel me now.

515
00:41:25,760 --> 00:41:29,150
Mrs. Luello is trying to help you.

516
00:41:29,360 --> 00:41:32,432
I would like you to try again,
but for this next issue-

517
00:41:32,640 --> 00:41:35,677
Next issue? No. No way. I quit.
Come on.

518
00:41:35,880 --> 00:41:38,235
No. No, I mean it. For the next
two years, just count me out.

519
00:41:38,440 --> 00:41:42,752
Hey, hey, Rand.
That's enough. Rand!

520
00:42:13,440 --> 00:42:18,798
Dr. Thompson. Dr. Thompson,
Nik Nik found this on Rand's bed.

521
00:42:23,520 --> 00:42:27,035
"Since it seems that I'm stuck
in Africa for two years,

522
00:42:27,240 --> 00:42:29,037
I would like to make
the best use of my time.

523
00:42:29,240 --> 00:42:34,189
I've read there is a new
anthropological dig on Lake Mizalacausie

524
00:42:34,400 --> 00:42:36,630
that is hiring workers.

525
00:42:36,840 --> 00:42:40,469
I'm going to apply for a job. Will
keep you advised. " Lake Mizalacausie?

526
00:42:40,680 --> 00:42:43,672
Lake Uzelazie. Dr. T, no one hikes
there from here. Rand will be lost.

527
00:42:43,880 --> 00:42:45,871
ELEANOR: Dr. Thompson?
Oh, for God sakes!

528
00:42:46,080 --> 00:42:48,150
ELEANOR: Dr. Thompson?
DR. THOMPSON: Yes, what? What?

529
00:42:48,360 --> 00:42:49,759
Did Rand leave a note?
Yes.

530
00:42:49,960 --> 00:42:52,952
He's gone off to God knows
where. Don't tell me that-

531
00:42:53,160 --> 00:42:55,515
Apparently, Val saw his note.
She thinks that Elsa's followed him.

532
00:42:55,720 --> 00:42:58,917
And now Vail’s gone too.
What are we gonna do?

533
00:42:59,120 --> 00:43:01,953
I'll call George Luello.
He has a big truck. Come.

534
00:43:02,160 --> 00:43:04,435
Let's go.
This is unbelievable.

535
00:43:11,120 --> 00:43:12,553
Okay.

536
00:43:18,880 --> 00:43:20,108
South.

537
00:43:23,800 --> 00:43:27,156
West. Okay.

538
00:43:41,000 --> 00:43:43,673
Elsa!

539
00:43:46,000 --> 00:43:48,434
Elsa!

540
00:43:52,360 --> 00:43:55,193
Elsa!

541
00:44:14,200 --> 00:44:16,350
[GROWLING]

542
00:44:25,800 --> 00:44:29,349
I know a few places we can look now, but I
don't expect to find anybody before tomorrow.

543
00:44:29,560 --> 00:44:31,596
We'll keep in touch.
DR. THOMPSON: I want to go with you.

544
00:44:31,800 --> 00:44:34,872
I appreciate how you feel,
but we work better on our own.

545
00:44:35,080 --> 00:44:37,594
Too many people will slow us down.
There must be something we can do.

546
00:44:37,800 --> 00:44:41,509
Please, stay here.
We'll find them.

547
00:44:41,760 --> 00:44:44,194
[ENGINE STARTS]

548
00:44:51,760 --> 00:44:53,637
RAND:
Got it going.

549
00:44:54,800 --> 00:44:57,109
[GROWLING]

550
00:45:08,960 --> 00:45:11,155
Elsa, that better be you.

551
00:45:17,960 --> 00:45:23,637
Hey, how are you?
What are you doing out here?

552
00:45:24,120 --> 00:45:27,157
What are you doing?
Are you out here looking for me?

553
00:45:31,520 --> 00:45:34,398
Oh, God. Oh, come here.

554
00:45:35,280 --> 00:45:37,794
Oh, I've never been so glad
to see anybody in my entire life.

555
00:45:38,000 --> 00:45:40,195
What are you doing here?
Oh, I was following Elsa,

556
00:45:40,400 --> 00:45:42,550
and she was tracking you.
Oh.

557
00:45:43,680 --> 00:45:46,877
You know, this isn't the way people
usually go to Lake Mizalacausie.

558
00:45:47,080 --> 00:45:50,436
I figured that out. It looked
like a shortcut on the map.

559
00:45:50,640 --> 00:45:54,997
You're also walking in a circle,
and it definitely takes longer that way.

560
00:45:57,720 --> 00:46:01,235
Don't feel badly. People get
lost out here all the time.

561
00:46:01,440 --> 00:46:05,592
There's lots of little box canyons
and landmarks that look alike.

562
00:46:06,240 --> 00:46:09,550
So, bwana, do you know
how to get out of here?

563
00:46:09,760 --> 00:46:11,910
I didn't say that.

564
00:46:15,200 --> 00:46:17,270
[GROWLING]

565
00:46:22,520 --> 00:46:24,556
Elsa!
No, Val, don't go out there.

566
00:46:24,760 --> 00:46:27,797
No.
No. No. She'll be killed.

567
00:46:28,480 --> 00:46:30,869
Val, she's a lion, okay?
She's got instincts too.

568
00:46:31,120 --> 00:46:33,076
VAL:
It's not enough.

569
00:46:37,160 --> 00:46:39,116
I'm sure. Come here.

570
00:46:40,280 --> 00:46:41,793
Come on.

571
00:46:56,200 --> 00:46:58,794
[SQU AWKING]

572
00:47:13,040 --> 00:47:14,792
Elsa's back.

573
00:47:15,040 --> 00:47:17,952
VAL:
Mm-hm. She came in at dawn.

574
00:47:24,120 --> 00:47:26,918
So are you gonna go
to Lake Mizalacausie?

575
00:47:27,120 --> 00:47:29,111
No, I don't think so.

576
00:47:29,360 --> 00:47:33,319
It's different
now that you're here.

577
00:47:34,440 --> 00:47:39,798
What I mean is, they'll probably
be looking for you and Elsa.

578
00:47:40,040 --> 00:47:45,034
Me and Elsa? What about you?
Okay, I started it,

579
00:47:46,080 --> 00:47:50,870
but I just think we should stick
together. Find our way back.

580
00:47:51,720 --> 00:47:55,315
Yeah. I didn't mean
to mess up your plans.

581
00:47:55,520 --> 00:47:58,398
I just couldn't let Elsa
run off like that.

582
00:47:59,320 --> 00:48:03,836
It's fine. It's all right.
I didn't want to go that badly.

583
00:48:04,040 --> 00:48:05,951
I was just angry.

584
00:48:06,680 --> 00:48:09,069
Are you still angry?

585
00:48:12,120 --> 00:48:13,997
Val, can you keep a secret?

586
00:48:17,280 --> 00:48:19,919
I'm starting to like it here.

587
00:48:51,600 --> 00:48:53,670
If this is the Balabi River,

588
00:48:53,880 --> 00:48:58,590
then we're somewhere in here.

589
00:48:58,800 --> 00:49:01,758
And home is that away.

590
00:49:13,960 --> 00:49:16,190
Oh, boy.

591
00:49:16,880 --> 00:49:22,034
Hey, Elsa, come on. Come on in too.
Elsa! Come on.

592
00:49:25,960 --> 00:49:29,032
Come on, girl.
Hey, come on.

593
00:49:31,120 --> 00:49:32,838
Oh, well.

594
00:49:34,320 --> 00:49:37,437
This fire is still warm.
Somebody was here.

595
00:49:37,640 --> 00:49:42,475
Yeah, this could have been Elsa's
spot. Maybe they're together.

596
00:49:42,680 --> 00:49:44,511
If it's them.

597
00:49:46,000 --> 00:49:48,275
Tea leaves. Val took
the Thermos with her.

598
00:49:48,480 --> 00:49:51,552
She always has pepper cupper.
Her dad's a Brit.

599
00:49:51,760 --> 00:49:55,116
Unbelievable. They're having a tea
party while we're sick with worry.

600
00:49:55,320 --> 00:49:57,470
At least they found each other.

601
00:49:57,680 --> 00:50:01,514
Look, their tracks go that way,
and the river's down there.

602
00:50:01,720 --> 00:50:04,075
If they made it to the river,
Val knows how to get home.

603
00:50:04,280 --> 00:50:07,192
Well, that is if Rand
wants to go home.

604
00:50:07,680 --> 00:50:09,557
Difficult days?

605
00:50:10,040 --> 00:50:11,519
Well...

606
00:50:11,880 --> 00:50:15,998
you know. Rand will never forgive me
for taking him away from his friends

607
00:50:16,200 --> 00:50:19,875
and his school and his
newsletter and this and that.

608
00:50:20,080 --> 00:50:21,832
Give him time.

609
00:50:22,040 --> 00:50:24,759
Who wouldn't want to trade
the city in for all this?

610
00:50:24,960 --> 00:50:29,351
Randolph Everett Thompson,
for one. Thank you.

611
00:50:30,840 --> 00:50:33,229
Sounds like a pretty unique fellow.

612
00:50:33,440 --> 00:50:38,036
Val pretends not to like him,
but she talks about him all the time.

613
00:50:38,240 --> 00:50:41,277
Well, no one can tell
Rand what to do.

614
00:50:42,600 --> 00:50:44,192
His mother...

615
00:50:45,640 --> 00:50:49,030
well, she was
much better with him.

616
00:50:49,240 --> 00:50:52,869
I really haven't been able
to reach him lately, since...

617
00:50:53,480 --> 00:50:59,077
You know, he resists just
about every single thing I say.

618
00:51:00,200 --> 00:51:02,998
I'm starting to
second-guess myself.

619
00:51:03,480 --> 00:51:05,914
Makes me think I'm
a pretty lousy father.

620
00:51:07,040 --> 00:51:11,670
Would it make you feel any better if I
told you he sounds like a normal teenager?

621
00:51:12,520 --> 00:51:16,069
Thanks. Look, I'm sorry. I don't
mean to dump all my problems on you.

622
00:51:16,280 --> 00:51:21,957
No, no, no, it has a familiar ring.
Remember, I've got one too.

623
00:51:23,000 --> 00:51:25,309
Oh, God!
What?

624
00:51:25,920 --> 00:51:28,434
I bet they spent
the night together.

625
00:51:31,600 --> 00:51:36,151
Oh, well, Eleanor, if you're suggesting that
my son would take advantage of your daughter...

626
00:51:36,360 --> 00:51:40,638
Please, David. It could have been
the other way around.

627
00:51:41,840 --> 00:51:42,989
Oh, boy.

628
00:52:27,840 --> 00:52:29,068
[VAL SCREAMING]

629
00:52:29,280 --> 00:52:31,430
Go! Go!

630
00:52:33,960 --> 00:52:35,632
Come on. Come on.

631
00:52:35,840 --> 00:52:38,752
[ROARING]

632
00:52:42,320 --> 00:52:45,551
[ROAR ECHOING]

633
00:53:47,520 --> 00:53:50,557
DR. THOMPSON: Thank you, Mr. Luello,
and I'm sorry for the trouble.

634
00:53:50,760 --> 00:53:52,273
I'm just glad everyone's back
in one piece.

635
00:53:52,480 --> 00:53:55,472
Thank you, George.
Don't do that again, huh?

636
00:53:56,520 --> 00:53:58,112
Val...

637
00:54:00,400 --> 00:54:02,277
Is that okay if I go to your house?
ELEANOR: Well, sure.

638
00:54:02,480 --> 00:54:06,393
Dad, I'll be at Vail’s, okay?
Just, uh, be home for dinner.

639
00:54:08,840 --> 00:54:10,831
Hold on, Rand.

640
00:54:11,840 --> 00:54:14,434
You and I have to have
a little talk.

641
00:54:23,000 --> 00:54:25,355
Now, could you please
explain to me

642
00:54:25,560 --> 00:54:29,075
why you went off
on this mission from hell?

643
00:54:31,680 --> 00:54:36,276
I was angry, and it was stupid.
And I admit it was dumb.

644
00:54:36,480 --> 00:54:41,838
Yes, it was dumb. It was dumb.
It was reckless and dumb.

645
00:54:42,680 --> 00:54:46,070
You're very lucky
there are no serious injuries.

646
00:54:47,360 --> 00:54:49,271
Very, very lucky.

647
00:54:50,440 --> 00:54:53,876
You've made your point.
Rand, what are you doing?!

648
00:54:54,120 --> 00:54:57,112
I don't understand
why you're behaving this way.

649
00:54:59,280 --> 00:55:03,956
I guess I was wrong to drag you out
here to this terrible, horrible place.

650
00:55:04,160 --> 00:55:06,674
Look at it. Terrible!

651
00:55:11,880 --> 00:55:13,632
I'm sorry.

652
00:55:15,960 --> 00:55:18,599
You're not to leave the grounds
unless I give you permission.

653
00:55:18,840 --> 00:55:20,876
Not even down the hill?

654
00:55:23,560 --> 00:55:26,552
Well, down the hill's okay, I guess.

655
00:55:31,600 --> 00:55:33,238
Thank you.

656
00:55:38,040 --> 00:55:40,554
[BLEATING]

657
00:55:45,680 --> 00:55:48,752
MAGILLA:
What is it? What's wrong?

658
00:55:53,320 --> 00:55:55,117
Oh.

659
00:55:57,760 --> 00:55:59,637
You again.

660
00:56:03,480 --> 00:56:05,436
No.

661
00:56:07,920 --> 00:56:11,435
Get away! Go away!

662
00:56:13,040 --> 00:56:14,758
Hey!

663
00:56:20,760 --> 00:56:22,239
Hey!

664
00:56:26,720 --> 00:56:31,191
[SINGING]

665
00:57:17,640 --> 00:57:18,868
Is Elsa okay?

666
00:57:19,120 --> 00:57:20,519
She ran off as soon as
the shooting started.

667
00:57:20,720 --> 00:57:23,678
The other lion wasn't so lucky.
Sorry, Val, but it's time now.

668
00:57:23,880 --> 00:57:27,316
What are you saying? You're gonna send Elsa to
a zoo because some male lion was pestering her?

669
00:57:27,520 --> 00:57:30,318
She's attracting them.
It's a dangerous situation.

670
00:57:30,520 --> 00:57:33,637
If the goatherd hadn't killed the lion,
the lion might have killed the goatherd.

671
00:57:33,840 --> 00:57:36,798
Now, I can't wait
till somebody gets hurt.

672
00:57:37,240 --> 00:57:39,993
I'm coming by for Elsa before dark.
You see that she's there.

673
00:57:40,200 --> 00:57:43,272
Ondine, sorry for the disruption.

674
00:57:56,400 --> 00:57:59,312
I'm sorry I ever started all this.

675
00:57:59,920 --> 00:58:02,354
I feel like letting every one
of them go right now.

676
00:58:02,560 --> 00:58:04,630
They would die, Val.

677
00:58:06,080 --> 00:58:07,832
They'd die.

678
00:58:08,960 --> 00:58:12,635
What you do for them is important.
You think so?

679
00:58:13,760 --> 00:58:16,274
But it's too hard when it's time
to say goodbye.

680
00:58:31,280 --> 00:58:33,475
Come on, Victor.

681
00:58:33,680 --> 00:58:36,592
Before somebody wants you
for their stupid zoo.

682
00:58:57,200 --> 00:58:59,395
Come on, Elsa. Up you go.

683
00:59:16,240 --> 00:59:17,832
How long untie she goes?

684
00:59:19,080 --> 00:59:21,878
A few days.
Can we come and see her?

685
00:59:22,240 --> 00:59:23,992
Of course.

686
00:59:54,080 --> 00:59:56,640
This doesn't feel right.

687
00:59:57,760 --> 00:59:59,637
Well, do you want to
go see her or not?

688
00:59:59,840 --> 01:00:01,239
I don't know.

689
01:00:01,440 --> 01:00:04,273
It might just make things worse.

690
01:00:04,840 --> 01:00:08,196
It's so weird seeing her
in a cage like this.

691
01:00:08,440 --> 01:00:10,670
Mm.

692
01:00:11,640 --> 01:00:13,198
Wait.

693
01:00:14,880 --> 01:00:17,440
Wait a minute, Val...

694
01:00:24,960 --> 01:00:28,111
RAND: Miss Luello,
what are you doing here?

695
01:00:28,320 --> 01:00:31,312
I live here. George is my brother.
Oh.

696
01:00:31,520 --> 01:00:32,999
I take it you've come to see Elsa?

697
01:00:33,240 --> 01:00:37,279
Uh, no. Actually we've come by
to see Mr. Luello.

698
01:00:37,480 --> 01:00:39,755
We'd like to release Elsa
back into the wild.

699
01:00:40,560 --> 01:00:43,996
Oh. Well, you'd better come in.

700
01:00:44,560 --> 01:00:48,599
The odds are very bad. Isn't it
best for Elsa to live in a zoo?

701
01:00:48,800 --> 01:00:52,429
And what kind of life is that?
Safe, secure.

702
01:00:52,680 --> 01:00:55,990
Like a prison?
She deserves a chance to be free.

703
01:00:56,200 --> 01:00:58,555
And we're willing
to work with her.

704
01:00:58,760 --> 01:01:01,911
Do you two have any idea
what you're getting yourselves into?

705
01:01:03,360 --> 01:01:05,555
Do you know how Elsa got
her name?

706
01:01:05,760 --> 01:01:08,320
Your brother named her
after the original Elsa,

707
01:01:08,560 --> 01:01:12,075
the lion that the lady raised-
Joy Adamson, yes.

708
01:01:12,280 --> 01:01:15,352
Have you read her book?
No.

709
01:01:16,160 --> 01:01:21,029
Before embarking on such a task,
I suggest you do your homework.

710
01:01:22,160 --> 01:01:26,392
And believe me, before asking
Mr. Luello for anything,

711
01:01:26,600 --> 01:01:30,479
you'd best be well-prepared.
Good luck and good reading.

712
01:01:30,680 --> 01:01:31,908
Thanks.
Thank you.

713
01:01:32,160 --> 01:01:33,912
You're welcome.

714
01:01:38,160 --> 01:01:40,720
The answer is no.

715
01:01:44,960 --> 01:01:47,235
And I don't appreciate your stunt
with the book.

716
01:01:47,440 --> 01:01:49,635
It will just give them wild ideas.

717
01:01:49,880 --> 01:01:52,110
At least they can prepare
a proper case.

718
01:01:52,360 --> 01:01:55,477
There is no case. That
situation was one in a million.

719
01:01:55,680 --> 01:01:57,750
This lion cannot survive
in the wild,

720
01:01:57,960 --> 01:02:00,190
and we can't have her
running around loose anymore.

721
01:02:00,440 --> 01:02:02,192
Her only hope is the zoo.

722
01:02:02,400 --> 01:02:06,075
George, how can you be so sure
she won't survive on her own?

723
01:02:06,280 --> 01:02:07,998
Doesn't she at least
deserve a chance?

724
01:02:08,200 --> 01:02:11,749
All this to do about one lion. I'm
responsible for millions of animals, Ondine.

725
01:02:11,960 --> 01:02:14,713
Why are you making such
a fuss about Elsa's future?

726
01:02:16,480 --> 01:02:20,678
It's not Elsa's future
that concerns me.

727
01:02:56,920 --> 01:03:00,833
RAND: Val and I have given this a
lot of careful thought, and we believe

728
01:03:01,040 --> 01:03:03,918
that Elsa has a legitimate chance
of survival in the wild

729
01:03:04,120 --> 01:03:07,510
if she is properly and systematically
introduced to the elements.

730
01:03:07,760 --> 01:03:11,878
Yes. My staff and I cover more
than two million acres of wildlife.

731
01:03:12,080 --> 01:03:15,072
We don't have so much time
for " properly and systematically. "

732
01:03:15,320 --> 01:03:17,993
We're only asking for a minimum
of support from your staff.

733
01:03:18,200 --> 01:03:20,475
Rand and I plan to do
all the training ourselves.

734
01:03:20,680 --> 01:03:21,999
And who's going to train you?

735
01:03:22,240 --> 01:03:24,879
Well, wait a minute. Joy
Adamson wasn't a trained expert.

736
01:03:25,080 --> 01:03:28,311
She loved her Elsa. She did the
best that she could, and it worked.

737
01:03:28,520 --> 01:03:31,751
We have the benefit of her experience. We
don't even have to make all the same mistakes.

738
01:03:32,000 --> 01:03:34,594
No, because you'll be making
plenty new ones of your own. Come.

739
01:03:34,800 --> 01:03:37,394
I want to show you something.

740
01:03:44,240 --> 01:03:48,438
All right. This is Elsa's normal diet,
meat with kibble,

741
01:03:48,640 --> 01:03:52,315
and this is what she'll be eating
in the wild, if she's lucky.

742
01:04:22,760 --> 01:04:25,752
All that proves is that she goes
for the easy stuff first.

743
01:04:26,000 --> 01:04:27,638
She would starve in the wild.

744
01:04:27,840 --> 01:04:31,310
VAL: No. She'd learn from the
other lions, be part of a pride.

745
01:04:31,560 --> 01:04:34,438
More like they'd kill her.
She belongs in a zoo.

746
01:04:34,680 --> 01:04:39,754
Val and I have made scientific observations in the
field that contradict your position, Mr. Luello.

747
01:04:40,000 --> 01:04:41,956
Scientific observations?

748
01:04:43,360 --> 01:04:44,759
While we were lost,

749
01:04:44,960 --> 01:04:48,077
we had a chance to spend some time
with Elsa in a natural environment.

750
01:04:48,280 --> 01:04:52,114
She didn't kill her food.
No, but she did fit in.

751
01:04:52,560 --> 01:04:54,312
And we think she found
a boyfriend.

752
01:04:54,520 --> 01:04:58,672
We see offshoot scientific
implications to this endeavor.

753
01:04:58,880 --> 01:05:03,112
Okay, one, how to influence animal
behavior, heredity versus environment,

754
01:05:03,320 --> 01:05:05,709
conditioning by kindness
or harshness.

755
01:05:05,960 --> 01:05:08,428
Offshoot scientific implications?

756
01:05:08,760 --> 01:05:11,832
Miss Luello said she'd give us credit.
I did?

757
01:05:12,040 --> 01:05:15,635
For special projects.
Uh, yes, I did say that.

758
01:05:15,840 --> 01:05:17,796
You gotta admit,
this is pretty special.

759
01:05:18,240 --> 01:05:21,118
Good try, but the answer is still no.

760
01:05:28,880 --> 01:05:32,395
Well, they are right, you know?
I beg your pardon?

761
01:05:33,200 --> 01:05:39,514
Well, there's no logical reason why
Elsa can't be successfully integrated.

762
01:05:39,720 --> 01:05:42,314
You see, the Adamson's experiment
changed everyone's thinking.

763
01:05:43,000 --> 01:05:46,197
I mean, since then,
there's been countless examples.

764
01:05:46,440 --> 01:05:50,513
Lions, wolves, even condors.

765
01:05:50,720 --> 01:05:53,678
Mr. Luello,
this is obviously your call.

766
01:05:53,880 --> 01:05:58,749
But speaking strictly as a scientist
and based on scientific evidence,

767
01:05:58,960 --> 01:06:02,236
Rand and Val have every reason
to expect success

768
01:06:02,480 --> 01:06:04,630
if they're given a chance.

769
01:06:12,200 --> 01:06:16,557
I'll give them two weeks.
Three. Please.

770
01:06:17,600 --> 01:06:22,037
All right. Three weeks.
Yes. Thank you.

771
01:06:30,200 --> 01:06:33,158
Thanks, Mom.
Yeah, thank you.

772
01:06:37,720 --> 01:06:40,632
Uncommonly bright children.
Yes.

773
01:06:40,840 --> 01:06:43,912
Impressive improvisational skills.

774
01:06:44,240 --> 01:06:46,231
That's one way of putting it.

775
01:06:47,840 --> 01:06:49,876
Like father, like son.

776
01:06:54,760 --> 01:06:57,479
Hi. Hi, girl.
Hey.

777
01:06:57,680 --> 01:06:59,159
Elsa!
Hey, Elsa, come here.

778
01:06:59,360 --> 01:07:00,588
Come here.

779
01:07:00,800 --> 01:07:02,836
VAL:
Hey, girl.

780
01:07:03,920 --> 01:07:05,433
RAND:
Welcome back.

781
01:07:06,880 --> 01:07:08,632
Now comes the hard part.

782
01:07:22,880 --> 01:07:25,519
[GROWLING]

783
01:07:32,760 --> 01:07:34,113
No, Elsa.

784
01:07:35,920 --> 01:07:37,638
She's hungry.

785
01:07:38,160 --> 01:07:39,832
She's supposed to be hungry.

786
01:07:40,080 --> 01:07:41,672
I think she's starving.

787
01:07:42,680 --> 01:07:46,639
Maybe she is, but tomorrow
she's gonna hunt her own dinner.

788
01:07:47,440 --> 01:07:49,032
Will she know how to do that?

789
01:07:50,240 --> 01:07:53,949
If she's hungry enough,
her natural instincts will take over.

790
01:07:54,440 --> 01:07:55,873
How do you know that?

791
01:07:57,160 --> 01:07:58,752
It's in the book.

792
01:08:08,120 --> 01:08:09,758
[CLATTERING]

793
01:08:28,320 --> 01:08:31,517
VAL: I should have let George
take her when she was still a baby.

794
01:08:31,720 --> 01:08:34,473
You don't mean that. Think
of what you would have missed.

795
01:08:34,680 --> 01:08:38,070
Think what I would have missed.
Fine for us, but all wrong for Elsa.

796
01:08:38,280 --> 01:08:41,317
I think she likes
the life that she's had,

797
01:08:41,520 --> 01:08:45,274
and she'll be okay once she
gets into the real wild country.

798
01:08:45,480 --> 01:08:48,233
She won't be ready.
Val, you're being so negative.

799
01:08:49,600 --> 01:08:51,431
VAL:
I love her. That's all.

800
01:08:55,760 --> 01:08:57,716
JOMO: Bye, everyone.
VAL: Bye.

801
01:08:57,920 --> 01:08:59,911
GINA: See you later.
RAND: Yeah, see you later.

802
01:09:00,120 --> 01:09:01,599
GINA: Good luck.
RAND: You coming, Gina?

803
01:09:01,800 --> 01:09:04,633
Oh, thanks, but I have other plans.
Other plans?

804
01:09:04,840 --> 01:09:07,593
You just- Never mind.

805
01:09:09,600 --> 01:09:10,999
All right.

806
01:09:11,480 --> 01:09:13,436
See you guys tonight, huh?

807
01:09:13,680 --> 01:09:15,432
Bye.
Bye.

808
01:09:17,920 --> 01:09:19,751
ALL: Bye.
RAND: Goodbye.

809
01:09:19,960 --> 01:09:21,837
Bye, guys.

810
01:09:37,720 --> 01:09:38,948
Come on, girl.
Come on.

811
01:09:39,360 --> 01:09:41,635
VAL: Come on, girl.
RAND: Come on. Come on.

812
01:09:42,080 --> 01:09:43,433
VAL:
Good girl.

813
01:09:47,720 --> 01:09:49,039
Good girl.

814
01:09:53,240 --> 01:09:55,800
[GROWLING]

815
01:10:22,920 --> 01:10:24,319
Why you doing that, Papa?

816
01:10:24,560 --> 01:10:25,959
Something new, Nik Nik.

817
01:10:26,160 --> 01:10:29,152
Desperate times call
for desperate measures.

818
01:10:37,760 --> 01:10:40,797
Yeah! Good girl!
Yes!

819
01:10:46,000 --> 01:10:47,956
She didn't kill it herself, though.

820
01:10:48,160 --> 01:10:50,833
But she stalked it,
and she brought it in.

821
01:10:51,320 --> 01:10:53,151
DR. THOMPSON:
And she is eating it.

822
01:10:53,360 --> 01:10:57,273
GEORGE: True, but Jomo won't be around
with his rifle next time to help her.

823
01:10:57,480 --> 01:10:59,914
DR. THOMPSON: He won't need to be.
I wish we had more time.

824
01:11:00,120 --> 01:11:03,476
Nope. Enough's enough.
She'll be ready.

825
01:11:03,680 --> 01:11:06,194
Saturday.
VAL AND RAND: Saturday.

826
01:11:06,400 --> 01:11:08,470
VAL:
Right, Mr. Luello.

827
01:11:13,320 --> 01:11:15,880
[COUGHS]

828
01:11:17,120 --> 01:11:19,554
I believe you're looking
for volunteers.

829
01:11:21,000 --> 01:11:22,831
Uh, well...

830
01:11:23,040 --> 01:11:26,396
Your field is virological research?
Yes.

831
01:11:26,840 --> 01:11:29,877
Well, I have some small knowledge
of the field myself.

832
01:11:30,080 --> 01:11:33,993
I'm certainly qualified to take some blood
samples and provide you with assistance.

833
01:11:34,240 --> 01:11:36,310
Dr. Thompson, isn't it?

834
01:11:36,520 --> 01:11:40,069
Yes, and you are?
I'm Selena Wilkinson.

835
01:11:40,440 --> 01:11:42,556
Oh.
Yes.

836
01:11:42,760 --> 01:11:46,116
Yes.
I believe Eleanor has spoken of me.

837
01:11:46,320 --> 01:11:48,595
Yeah.
If you don't want my help,

838
01:11:48,800 --> 01:11:50,518
believe me, I'll understand.

839
01:11:50,720 --> 01:11:52,438
But I wanted to offer it anyway.

840
01:11:53,440 --> 01:11:55,670
You see, I've been sitting
at home for a month,

841
01:11:55,880 --> 01:11:57,791
pouting over your good fortune,

842
01:11:58,000 --> 01:11:59,911
and there's something
wrong with that.

843
01:12:00,560 --> 01:12:04,030
If I were in your shoes and
qualified help were around the corner,

844
01:12:04,240 --> 01:12:06,470
I'd wonder why I
didn't step forward.

845
01:12:08,640 --> 01:12:10,835
Well, I really don't know what to say.

846
01:12:11,080 --> 01:12:13,196
Well, say yes, doctor.

847
01:12:13,440 --> 01:12:15,795
Oh, yes, please.
I mean, of course.

848
01:12:16,040 --> 01:12:19,430
Good. Robert, in here.

849
01:12:38,600 --> 01:12:40,591
This should come in handy.

850
01:12:40,800 --> 01:12:43,837
Yes. Yes, indeed.

851
01:13:08,120 --> 01:13:09,519
That thing suits you.

852
01:13:09,760 --> 01:13:13,309
Well, I wouldn't be caught
dead riding this in the city.

853
01:13:14,520 --> 01:13:16,556
From Future Business
Leaders of America.

854
01:13:16,760 --> 01:13:19,672
Yeah. Let's see.

855
01:13:20,480 --> 01:13:22,311
Yeah.

856
01:13:23,000 --> 01:13:25,468
Collins. Collins Brokerage.

857
01:13:26,640 --> 01:13:29,154
The apprenticeship. I got it.
They want me in the office on Monday.

858
01:13:29,400 --> 01:13:32,836
Wow, an airplane ticket.
This outfit doesn't fool around, huh?

859
01:13:33,040 --> 01:13:36,112
Room and board, a salary.
Dad, this is an incredible opportunity!

860
01:13:36,320 --> 01:13:39,278
Sure sounds like one,
if that's what you want.

861
01:13:39,520 --> 01:13:40,999
It's okay?

862
01:13:42,800 --> 01:13:45,234
Thank you. Thank you.

863
01:13:46,080 --> 01:13:48,594
Hey, uh, what about
your friend there?

864
01:13:50,800 --> 01:13:56,989
Elsa. Well, I'm gonna miss
the final release, of course, but...

865
01:13:57,200 --> 01:13:59,555
Come on, Elsa!
She's gonna be all right.

866
01:14:00,480 --> 01:14:03,517
Dad, this is
an incredible opportunity.

867
01:14:03,720 --> 01:14:06,393
This is a once in a lifetime chance.
Come on, girl!

868
01:14:17,680 --> 01:14:19,989
Geri, I didn't plan it
this way, okay?

869
01:14:23,520 --> 01:14:25,670
I didn't want to come
to Africa in the first place.

870
01:14:26,040 --> 01:14:27,393
Will you come back?

871
01:14:28,000 --> 01:14:32,039
Yeah. Yeah, I'll come back
to see, uh...

872
01:14:32,240 --> 01:14:34,800
You know, to see Dad
and Gina. You.

873
01:14:35,000 --> 01:14:37,992
But not Elsa. She won't be here.

874
01:14:41,240 --> 01:14:43,037
No.

875
01:14:43,920 --> 01:14:45,319
What about Val?

876
01:14:46,760 --> 01:14:48,796
Well, I'll come and see Val too.

877
01:14:49,040 --> 01:14:51,998
No, I mean, have you told her?

878
01:14:53,800 --> 01:14:55,711
It's on my agenda.

879
01:15:01,920 --> 01:15:03,638
Big day for Homer, huh?

880
01:15:03,840 --> 01:15:06,752
His idea of freedom
is the palm of my hand.

881
01:15:11,120 --> 01:15:15,477
Listen, uh, about
tomorrow and Elsa.

882
01:15:18,520 --> 01:15:20,397
Uh...

883
01:15:22,040 --> 01:15:24,235
Something's come up...

884
01:15:25,040 --> 01:15:26,268
and I can't go.

885
01:15:27,720 --> 01:15:29,790
What?

886
01:15:30,760 --> 01:15:32,751
I have...

887
01:15:34,000 --> 01:15:39,393
I have an incredible chance to
intern at a brokerage back home.

888
01:15:41,320 --> 01:15:45,233
They sent me an airplane ticket
and everything.

889
01:15:48,480 --> 01:15:51,153
I guess this is goodbye for now.

890
01:15:52,920 --> 01:15:54,353
I'll write you.

891
01:15:55,560 --> 01:15:58,393
I hope you'll write me and tell me
how things work with Elsa.

892
01:15:58,600 --> 01:16:01,160
Elsa will be
in the Rotterdam Zoo.

893
01:16:01,720 --> 01:16:04,439
RAND:
But it's all set up with George.

894
01:16:04,680 --> 01:16:07,433
You and I were going
to free Elsa together.

895
01:16:11,640 --> 01:16:13,835
I can't believe how wrong
I was about you.

896
01:16:14,560 --> 01:16:16,835
You had me completely fooled.

897
01:16:17,760 --> 01:16:19,955
I thought you really cared...

898
01:16:20,880 --> 01:16:22,313
about Elsa.

899
01:16:22,520 --> 01:16:28,709
I do. I do care, but this is a dream
that I had long before I met you or Elsa.

900
01:16:28,920 --> 01:16:30,797
And if you're suggesting
that I pass this up-

901
01:16:31,040 --> 01:16:32,359
I'm not suggesting anything.

902
01:16:32,760 --> 01:16:36,548
Maybe this is hard for someone
like you to understand.

903
01:16:36,760 --> 01:16:41,231
That's right. It's hard for someone
like me to understand. Goodbye, Rand.

904
01:16:41,440 --> 01:16:44,238
Val.
There's nothing to say.

905
01:16:44,440 --> 01:16:47,273
Just go on home
and have your dream.

906
01:16:47,480 --> 01:16:49,232
I want to forget
I ever knew you.

907
01:17:04,160 --> 01:17:05,718
Rand?

908
01:17:09,880 --> 01:17:11,472
Something wrong?

909
01:17:14,200 --> 01:17:16,839
Yeah, it's Val.

910
01:17:17,400 --> 01:17:19,436
Oh.

911
01:17:21,600 --> 01:17:23,909
She must be upset.

912
01:17:24,800 --> 01:17:26,916
Yeah, she is.

913
01:17:35,160 --> 01:17:37,276
You know...

914
01:17:38,240 --> 01:17:40,071
I've been thinking about this...

915
01:17:46,640 --> 01:17:49,108
and Collins Brokerage is okay.

916
01:17:49,320 --> 01:17:51,959
It's not top of the line
by any means.

917
01:17:52,720 --> 01:17:56,872
And if you're serious about this, I
don't want you settling for second best.

918
01:17:58,960 --> 01:18:00,279
Maybe the timing's wrong.

919
01:18:00,480 --> 01:18:02,994
No, you're right about Collins.

920
01:18:03,200 --> 01:18:06,351
The market is down a little bit.
Yeah, mm-hm.

921
01:18:06,560 --> 01:18:10,439
You can always reapply in summer.
Yeah. I suppose I could sign up.

922
01:18:12,200 --> 01:18:14,714
You know, I hate to go
back on my word, Rand.

923
01:18:14,960 --> 01:18:16,632
But...

924
01:18:17,640 --> 01:18:20,518
I'm going to have to insist
that you pass this up.

925
01:18:22,080 --> 01:18:23,399
If you're insisting, then...

926
01:18:24,040 --> 01:18:27,191
I'm sorry, Rand, but I do.

927
01:18:33,960 --> 01:18:36,190
I understand.

928
01:18:40,000 --> 01:18:41,638
So, uh...

929
01:18:41,840 --> 01:18:46,630
I guess this means that
I'll be here for Elsa's release.

930
01:18:48,320 --> 01:18:49,548
Oh, I guess so.

931
01:18:52,720 --> 01:18:54,756
I, uh...

932
01:18:55,240 --> 01:18:58,550
I don't suppose there's any
chance that you could come with us?

933
01:19:00,240 --> 01:19:03,312
Oh, uh, well, I'll be there.

934
01:19:21,840 --> 01:19:23,717
RAND:
Val. VaI!

935
01:19:24,800 --> 01:19:26,233
Come here.

936
01:19:26,440 --> 01:19:29,352
I'm not gonna go. I made up
my mind. No, I'm gonna stay.

937
01:19:29,560 --> 01:19:31,710
Yeah?
I'm staying.

938
01:19:34,240 --> 01:19:35,912
I'm staying.

939
01:19:40,520 --> 01:19:42,397
Hi, Dad.
Hi.

940
01:19:44,560 --> 01:19:47,279
What are you doing here?
Sure do get involved in your work.

941
01:19:47,480 --> 01:19:51,473
I've been here for two days already.
So have Azizi and Maleaka.

942
01:19:51,880 --> 01:19:55,793
Oh, it's gotta be the uniform. It must
be the uniform. I'm not that oblivious.

943
01:19:56,000 --> 01:19:58,992
Oh, yes. Yes, I'm afraid you are.
It's been very amusing to watch.

944
01:20:01,480 --> 01:20:03,038
Look. Whose idea is this?

945
01:20:03,240 --> 01:20:04,719
This is a clinic. People die here.

946
01:20:04,920 --> 01:20:07,957
I don't think Gina's ready for this.
David, David, look at her.

947
01:20:08,200 --> 01:20:11,875
She has extraordinary
patience and skill.

948
01:20:12,960 --> 01:20:17,476
She is not a little girl anymore.
Or haven't you noticed that either?

949
01:20:18,520 --> 01:20:21,478
So you think you can handle
having me as a coworker?

950
01:20:23,200 --> 01:20:26,749
Absolutely. Actually, this is
something I've been wanting you to do

951
01:20:26,960 --> 01:20:29,394
for some time. Now, maybe
you can get your boss

952
01:20:29,600 --> 01:20:32,114
to give you a couple of days off
to see Elsa set free.

953
01:20:32,320 --> 01:20:36,074
Oh, Dad, I love Elsa,
but duty calls.

954
01:20:37,400 --> 01:20:39,197
Here you go, let me take these.

955
01:20:43,400 --> 01:20:45,072
Well, I don't know
what your schedule is-

956
01:20:45,280 --> 01:20:46,713
I would love to.

957
01:21:15,600 --> 01:21:16,794
Come on.

958
01:21:17,040 --> 01:21:18,268
Come on. Get down.
Elsa, come.

959
01:21:18,480 --> 01:21:19,674
Right over there.

960
01:21:20,440 --> 01:21:23,159
VAL:
Elsa, come on. Come on.

961
01:21:23,480 --> 01:21:25,038
RAND:
It's not gonna work.

962
01:21:52,000 --> 01:21:54,639
RAND:
Come on. There you go.

963
01:21:55,800 --> 01:21:57,313
Oh, boy.

964
01:22:08,120 --> 01:22:09,519
Elsa.

965
01:22:15,840 --> 01:22:18,354
VAL: Go, girl.
RAND: Come on, Elsa.

966
01:22:23,880 --> 01:22:26,678
[BARKING]

967
01:22:37,720 --> 01:22:39,312
They're hurting her.

968
01:22:43,200 --> 01:22:44,428
Are you gonna let
them kill her?!

969
01:22:44,640 --> 01:22:46,471
[GUN SHOOTS]

970
01:22:48,720 --> 01:22:50,153
VAL:
Elsa.

971
01:22:55,560 --> 01:22:57,551
Elsa.

972
01:22:57,760 --> 01:22:59,716
Geri.

973
01:23:06,960 --> 01:23:10,157
It's nothing serious.
It's just a few scratches.

974
01:23:10,360 --> 01:23:12,510
They might have torn her to pieces.

975
01:23:12,720 --> 01:23:15,359
I can't believe those runts
were attacking a lion.

976
01:23:15,560 --> 01:23:18,711
She smells of civilization.
They knew she was an easy mark.

977
01:23:18,920 --> 01:23:21,832
No. She wasn't easy.
She put up a good fight untie...

978
01:23:22,040 --> 01:23:25,350
Yeah, but it didn't work,
and it's not going to work.

979
01:23:25,840 --> 01:23:28,274
We go back to Shama tomorrow.

980
01:23:29,120 --> 01:23:30,758
You promised three weeks.

981
01:23:30,960 --> 01:23:32,518
What's the point
of wasting more time?

982
01:23:32,720 --> 01:23:35,792
The point is you promised.
Three weeks is what we agreed on.

983
01:23:36,000 --> 01:23:39,470
We still have 10 days left.
A lot can happen in 10 days.

984
01:23:39,680 --> 01:23:41,511
A deal is a deal.

985
01:23:44,400 --> 01:23:45,833
All right.

986
01:24:00,040 --> 01:24:02,838
I shouldn't have shot the gun.
I wanted to.

987
01:24:03,040 --> 01:24:06,635
Yeah, but you didn't.
George is right.

988
01:24:07,840 --> 01:24:10,149
In a zoo, she'd be safe.

989
01:24:11,680 --> 01:24:14,433
That's the easiest way out
for everybody.

990
01:24:16,240 --> 01:24:18,435
I don't think it's the best for Elsa.

991
01:24:36,640 --> 01:24:38,198
Elsa.

992
01:24:45,920 --> 01:24:47,353
Elsa.

993
01:24:48,680 --> 01:24:50,796
No, Elsa. Elsa!

994
01:24:51,280 --> 01:24:54,352
This is unbearable.
She has to hunt for her own food.

995
01:24:54,560 --> 01:24:56,630
In the meantime,
she's gonna starve to death.

996
01:24:56,880 --> 01:24:59,155
If we feed her,
we're sending her to a zoo.

997
01:26:05,280 --> 01:26:07,953
You remind me of Elsa, Rand.

998
01:26:08,920 --> 01:26:10,592
I miss her.

999
01:26:11,960 --> 01:26:14,190
It's been three days.

1000
01:26:14,760 --> 01:26:16,910
Isn't that what we wanted?

1001
01:26:17,840 --> 01:26:19,990
Something may have happened.

1002
01:26:21,000 --> 01:26:23,195
She was weak from not having eaten.

1003
01:26:23,400 --> 01:26:24,958
What if something attacked her?

1004
01:26:25,720 --> 01:26:30,430
Or she's just starving.
Okay, let's go look.

1005
01:27:12,040 --> 01:27:14,076
There! Just to the left.

1006
01:27:24,160 --> 01:27:26,151
It's her.
Let me see, let me see.

1007
01:27:29,360 --> 01:27:31,749
Oh, yeah, that's her.

1008
01:27:32,000 --> 01:27:33,831
ALL:
Yes!

1009
01:27:38,080 --> 01:27:39,308
Oh, man.

1010
01:28:13,120 --> 01:28:14,758
We need some symphony music.

1011
01:28:15,000 --> 01:28:17,514
[ROARS]

1012
01:28:21,240 --> 01:28:22,639
Complications.

1013
01:28:36,080 --> 01:28:37,274
Uh-oh.

1014
01:28:41,760 --> 01:28:43,318
Come on. Come on.

1015
01:29:47,320 --> 01:29:49,436
I think she's found
a new home.

1016
01:29:51,720 --> 01:29:53,597
She's not the only one.

1017
01:30:03,960 --> 01:30:05,234
Let's go.

1018
01:30:56,480 --> 01:31:01,315
[DRUMS BEATING]

1019
01:31:09,880 --> 01:31:13,793
[CHEERING]

